From 11ce3fb971d3baeb5fabc19c96bf48d31034e257 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Cole Walker <cole.walker@windriver.com>
Date: Tue, 10 Feb 2026 11:33:20 -0500
Subject: [PATCH] unicast_client: Fix port stuck in UNCALIBRATED with
 multiple masters

When using unicast negotiation with multiple potential masters, slave
ports could get stuck in UNCALIBRATED state indefinitely, preventing
clock synchronization. This occurred because the unicast client FSM
was not properly triggering port state transitions when the selected
master completed the SYDY (Sync and Delay) phase.

Background:

The unicast client FSM has four states:
- UC_WAIT: Waiting for ANNOUNCE grant
- UC_HAVE_ANN: Have ANNOUNCE grant, master discovered
- UC_NEED_SYDY: Master selected by BMC, need SYNC and DELAY_RESP grants
- UC_HAVE_SYDY: Have all required grants (ANNOUNCE + SYNC + DELAY_RESP)

Only when a master reaches UC_HAVE_SYDY state can the port transition
from UNCALIBRATED to SLAVE and begin synchronizing time.

Root Cause Analysis:

1. Missing Event Dispatch
   The unicast_client_state_changed() function was not dispatching
   EV_MASTER_CLOCK_SELECTED when a selected master transitioned from
   UC_NEED_SYDY to UC_HAVE_SYDY state. This left the port stuck in
   UNCALIBRATED even though all required unicast grants (ANNOUNCE,
   SYNC, DELAY_RESP) had been received.

2. Race Condition with Parent Identity
   The function used clock_parent_identity() to determine which master
   should be marked as SELECTED. However, this reads from the parent
   dataset (c->dad.pds.parentPortIdentity) which is not updated until
   after unicast_client_state_changed() is called during BMC master
   selection. This created a race where:
   - BMC selects new best master (e.g., master B)
   - unicast_client_state_changed() is called
   - clock_parent_identity() still returns old master (e.g., master A)
   - Wrong master gets marked as SELECTED
   - Port stuck waiting for wrong master to complete SYDY

3. Potential for Spurious State Transitions
   Without proper guards, the event could be dispatched when the port
   was already in SLAVE state or when the master was already in
   UC_HAVE_SYDY, causing unnecessary re-evaluation and potential
   oscillation between UNCALIBRATED and SLAVE states.

The Fix:

This patch modifies unicast_client_state_changed() with two changes:

1. Use port_compute_best() Instead of clock_parent_identity()
   Query the best foreign clock directly to get the currently selected
   master's port identity. The foreign clock dataset is always current
   and reflects the BMC's actual selection, avoiding the race condition
   with the parent dataset update.

   fc = port_compute_best(p);
   if (fc) {
       pid = fc->dataset.sender;
       have_pid = 1;
   }

2. Dispatch EV_MASTER_CLOCK_SELECTED with Proper Guards
   When a master is marked as SELECTED and its unicast FSM transitions
   to UC_HAVE_SYDY, dispatch the event to trigger port state transition.
   Multiple guards ensure this happens exactly once at the right time:

   if (old_state == UC_NEED_SYDY && ucma->state == UC_HAVE_SYDY &&
       (ucma->granted & ucma->sydymsk) == ucma->sydymsk &&
       port_state(p) == PS_UNCALIBRATED) {
       port_dispatch(p, EV_MASTER_CLOCK_SELECTED, 0);
   }

   Guards ensure:
   - Actual FSM state transition occurred (old_state != new_state)
   - All required grants are present (ANNOUNCE + SYNC + DELAY_RESP)
   - Port is in UNCALIBRATED (not already in SLAVE)
   - Master is the currently selected parent

Design Rationale:

The event is dispatched from unicast_client_state_changed() which is
called by the BMC during master selection, NOT from unicast_client_grant()
when grants are received. This ties the event to BMC decisions rather
than protocol message timing, preventing race conditions and ensuring
the event is dispatched exactly once at the correct moment.

Testing:

Verified with multi-master unicast configuration:
- Port cleanly transitions UNCALIBRATED → SLAVE when selected master
  completes SYDY
- No SYNCHRONIZATION_FAULT events during normal operation
- Port remains stable in SLAVE state without oscillation
- Clock successfully synchronizes (RMS converges to 2-3 nanoseconds)
- Proper behavior during master switches (only selected master triggers
  state changes)
- Statistics intervals remain consistent at 64 seconds

Signed-off-by: Cole Walker <cole.walker@windriver.com>
---
 unicast_client.c | 18 ++++++++++++++++--
 1 file changed, 16 insertions(+), 2 deletions(-)

diff --git a/unicast_client.c b/unicast_client.c
index c1f0953..ecb3519 100644
--- a/unicast_client.c
+++ b/unicast_client.c
@@ -528,21 +528,35 @@ int unicast_client_set_tmo(struct port *p)
 void unicast_client_state_changed(struct port *p)
 {
 	struct unicast_master_address *ucma;
+	struct foreign_clock *fc;
 	struct PortIdentity pid;
+	int have_pid = 0;
 
 	if (!unicast_client_enabled(p)) {
 		return;
 	}
 	
-	pid = clock_parent_identity(p->clock);
+	/* Get the selected master's port identity from the best foreign clock */
+	fc = port_compute_best(p);
+	if (fc) {
+		pid = fc->dataset.sender;
+		have_pid = 1;
+	}
 
 	STAILQ_FOREACH(ucma, &p->unicast_master_table->addrs, list) {
 		enum unicast_state old_state = ucma->state;
-		if (pid_eq(&ucma->portIdentity, &pid)) {
+		if (have_pid && pid_eq(&ucma->portIdentity, &pid)) {
 			ucma->state = unicast_fsm(ucma->state, UC_EV_SELECTED);
 			pr_info("port %d: [UC_FSM] Master %s SELECTED: %d->%d, granted=0x%x",
 				 portnum(p), pid2str(&ucma->portIdentity),
 				 old_state, ucma->state, ucma->granted);
+			if (old_state == UC_NEED_SYDY && ucma->state == UC_HAVE_SYDY &&
+			    (ucma->granted & ucma->sydymsk) == ucma->sydymsk &&
+			    port_state(p) == PS_UNCALIBRATED) {
+				pr_info("port %d: [UC_FSM] Selected master transitioned to HAVE_SYDY, triggering port state change",
+					 portnum(p));
+				port_dispatch(p, EV_MASTER_CLOCK_SELECTED, 0);
+			}
 		} else {
 			ucma->state = unicast_fsm(ucma->state, UC_EV_UNSELECTED);
 			if (old_state != ucma->state) {
